04039nam a22006615i 9781501735349DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2019    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017353497 a10.7591/97815017353492doi  a(DE-B1597)533809  a(OCoLC)1129183763  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0240002bisacsh1 aFrench, Rebecca Redwood, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Golden Yoke :bthe Legal Cosmology of Buddhist Tibet /cRebecca Redwood French. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (424 p.) :b50 Glatffelter Supple Opaque  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tA Note on Tibetan Translation, Transliteration, and Citation -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE. THE CONTEXT OF TIBET -- tPART TWO. THE COSMOLOGY OF LAW -- tPART THREE. REPORTS FROM THE COUNTRYSIDE -- tPART FOUR. REPORTS FROM THE CENTRAL BUREAUCRACY -- tPART FIVE. CRIMES AND OFFICIALS -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tTibetan Word Index -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Golden Yoke is a remarkable achievement. It is the first elaboration of the legal, cultural, and ideological dimensions of precommunist Tibetan jurisprudence, a unique legal system that maintains its secularism within a thoroughly Buddhist setting. Layer by layer, Rebecca Redwood French reconstructs the daily operation of law in Tibet before the Chinese invasion in 1959.In the Tibetans' own words, French identifies their courts, symbols, and personnel and traces the procedures for petitioning and filing documents. There are stories here from judges, legal conciliators, and lay people about murder, property disputes, and divorce. French shows that Tibetan law is deeply embedded in its Buddhist culture and that the system evolved not from the rules and judgments but from what people actually do and say. In what amounts to a fully developed cosmology, she describes the cultural foundation that informs the system: myths, notions of time and conflux, inner morality, language patterns, rituals, use of space, symbols, and concepts.Based on extensive readings of Tibetan legal documents and codes, interviews with Tibetan scholars, and the reminiscences of Tibetans at home and in exile, this generously illustrated, elegantly written work is a model of outstanding research. French combines the talents of a legal anthropologist with those of a former law practitioner to develop a new field of study that has implications for other judicial systems, including our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Eastern.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501735349423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501735349.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG